<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by The Motivation Charitable Trust</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><div style="border-bottom-color:#4f81bd; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:1pt; clear:both; margin:0pt 0pt 15pt"><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:15pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Written evidence submitted by The Motivation Charitable Trust </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:15pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; padding-bottom:4pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Executive Summary: </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">Disabled people’s access to assistive devices is a human right recognized by the United Nations. However, for disabled individuals in the developing world, </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">assistive devices are often difficult to obtain, and</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">,</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> when they are available, inappropriate for both the user and the environment. </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">An appropriate assistive device can dramatically improve the health and quality of life of the user, but an inappropriate on</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">e can cause serious and potentially deadly medical complications. Despite this, assistive devices receive little attention from institutional development agencies. Furthermore, development projects</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> are frequently designed without consideration of the needs</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> of disabled people and as a result, disabled people are excluded and marginalized</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> from much-needed programmes</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">. The Department for International Development is called upon to adhere to international guidelines on disability, include both disabled people an</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">d attention to assistive devices in development projects and to ensure that all assistive devices used in their programmes are appropriate for the needs of the beneficiaries. Without this, development efforts will fail</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> by neglecting </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">a </span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt">vulnerable portion of</span><span style="color:#17365d; font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; letter-spacing:0.25pt"> the world. </span></p></div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Submission Author: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Motivation is an international development charity supporting people with mobility disabilities. Our high-quality, low-cost wheelchairs are designed specifically for use in developing countries. Teamed with our innovative </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">training programmes, our wheelchairs transform lives, giving disabled people independence, confidence and hope for the future. Motivation has 22 years of experience in wheelchair service development in low-income countries, and is widely recognized as a le</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ader in the sector. We are particularly well-known for our expertise in the following areas:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Design, production and supply of low-cost wheelchairs, seating products, cushions and tricycles</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Training of wheelchair service staff in assessment, prescription, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssembly and fitting of wheelchairs</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wheelchair service training development</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Capacity building for establishment and management of wheelchair services</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Wheelchair service advocacy with national governments, health ministries, INGOs and local NGOs</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Peer-to-Peer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> training in wheelchair skills and independent living (courses taught by wheelchair users themselves)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written Evidence:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Assistive devices are products and technology that maintain or improve disabled people’s functional capabilities. These devices assis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t disabled individuals in achieving daily life tasks, education, work, recreational activities and communication, amongst other things. Without assistive devices, many disabled people experience a loss of independence and a decrease in their quality of lif</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is especially true for those in the developing world, where assistive devices are in short supply due to high cost and low levels of production or importation. Assistive devices are a pre-condition for impact in all areas of development—without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">them disabled people cannot participate in development efforts or realise their basic human rights. As many as 70 million people need a wheelchair globally – representing approximately 1% of any population. Despite these figures, the World Health Organisat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion (WHO) states that in most low and middle-income countries, only 5-15% of people who require an assistive device actually have access to them, and, in cases where devices are available, they are frequently expensive, low quality and of inappropriate des</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ign for both the user and the environment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Article 20 of the United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities recognises the provision of assistive devices as a human right, in order to “ensure and promote the full realization of all h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uman rights and fundamental freedoms for all persons with disabilities without discrimination of any kind on the basis of disability.”</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  For people with many different kinds of disability, appropriate assistive devices are the first step to their survival,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which in turn, leads to their empowerment and, ultimately, inclusion. Appropriate assistive devices enable disabled people to participate in daily activities, attend work or school, and participate actively in their community. They reduce dependence and i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mprove both physical health and quality of life.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For example, a baseline study from a DFID-funded project in Uganda recently found that the parents of children with mobility disabilities (primarily cerebral palsy) frequently reported that once a child became too heavy to carry (as they lacked assistive d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evices), it was necessary to leave the child at home all day, which reinforced their exclusion and stigma, and denied the child their right to education and participation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">social life. Accordingly, the study found that of the children included in the bas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eline, only 23% of disabled children (and as few as 6% of children with cerebral palsy) were in school. The study also noted that 72% of parents/carers of disabled children were regularly experiencing difficulties obtaining necessary support, and as many a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s 78% of parents/carers lacked knowledge about the causes of their child’s disability, which hindered them in providing the best care possible for their child. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, an impact assessment undertaken across four countries (Pakistan, South Sudan, Eth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iopia, and Sri Lanka) as part of a recently concluded 4-year programme found that 100% of the 354 beneficiaries surveyed reported a positive change in their quality of life after receiving an assistive device. They also noted improved access to their local</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> environment, increased levels of independence, significant positive change to their health, and wider integration into social and economic life. The parents/carers of disabled children also reported that their own quality of life and health had improved a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a result of their children’s new device. Assistive devices are more than just products; they are catalysts to inclusion and participation and a crucial foundation for the elimination of poverty, for without them, disabled individuals with disabilities ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nnot participate in economic and social life. One beneficiary in the programme referenced above who received an assistive device said, “When I am on my tricycle, I don’t feel at all like a disabled person. This tricycle makes me forget my disability. It is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> my aeroplane that flies me to every destination.” Another said, “Going to school and meeting my friends is the most joyful thing. Thanks to my wheelchair I do all.”</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A stronger focus from DFID on reaching disabled people is essential to begin to realise t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hese benefits for all disabled people. Despite being the first major development agency to publish a paper linking poverty and disability in 2000, DFID’s work on disability remains largely hidden. Over a decade has passed since that ground breaking paper w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as released, and yet DFID has not joined other major institutional donors in developing significant programmes aimed at disabled people. DFID staff and country offices are often unaware of disability programmes being carried out by NGOs and CSOs. As a resu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lt, DFID’s work to reduce poverty will have limited impact if it does not consider the needs of disabled people – a particularly vulnerable portion of the population. Furthermore, DFID attention to assistive devices needs to include a range of products, su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ch as prosthetics and orthotics, wheelchairs and cushions, tricycles and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">urinary management products, which are essential for maintaining human rights and dignity.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The disability sector would welcome a special funding stream earmarked to support disabled </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">people (as USAID currently has) as a contribution to the significant investment needs in this area. DFID must work to ensure inclusive structures accessible to disabled people. Accessibility—through both assistive devices and project design—is key for main</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">streaming and inclusion to work effectively. It is also crucial that disabled people are not abandoned during responses to emergencies and disasters. Significant numbers of people injured in disasters and emergencies will need temporary or permanent use of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a wheelchair or other assistive devices. A substantial number of disabled people will lose their assistive products during the crisis and as a result are unable to access other emergency services such as food, shelter, and medical aid—making them one of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he most vulnerable groups (immobile, excluded from relief efforts, dependent on others, and at risk of serious health complications). Assistive devices that do arrive are normally second-hand donated ones that do not meet international standards, are not a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ppropriate for the challenging post-disaster environment, and are not adaptable to the users’ needs, which can lead to further health complications and even death. It is crucial that international development agencies like DFID include disabled people in t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heir responses to crises to ensure they receive medical care, food, shelter, and appropriate assistive devices. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 15.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Inappropriate wheelchairs and assistive devices not adhering to international standards are an unfortunately common feature of programmes aime</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d at disabled people. Such products are not designed for the users’ environments and frequently break. They can lead to multiple and serious secondary health problems. For example, a child with cerebral palsy requires additional postural support that most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">donated wheelchairs do not possess. A lack of such support causes the child to feel unstable, straining the muscles and causing exhaustion and discomfort, impeding their ability to play and attend school. Life threatening chest infections can occur when fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">od and drink are inhaled into the lungs as a result of the difficulty in coordinating swallowing whilst the child’s head and neck are not stable. The child’s skin can also break down due to their body weight being unevenly distributed in the wheelchair; th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is can lead to potentially deadly pressure ulcers, a frequent cause of death for mobility-disabled people. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabled people also often have other specific needs, such as pressure cushions and urinary management products, which go unmet and as a result significantly reduce an individual’s quality of life. The WHO notes that “studies have shown that assistive tech</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nologies, when appropriate to the user and the user’s environment, have a significant impact on the level of independence and participation which people with disabilities are able to achieve.”</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">USAID and the WHO, with the assistance of several NGOs, incl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uding Motivation, have released a joint paper on the provision of mobility devices in less resourced settings. The paper is intended to be “a step towards implementation of the Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD) related to persona</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l mobility,” with the recognition that the needs of disabled people are not being met, especially in the developing world. It has the potential to act as a guide for countries, NGOs and development agencies in meeting the rights outlined in the CRPD and DF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ID is urged to take the joint paper’s findings into consideration for its international strategy and programmes. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The disability sector calls on DFID to guarantee that appropriate wheelchairs and other assistive devices adhering to the internationally rec</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ognized WHO standards are used in all DFID programmes. The needs of the user, both physical and mental, are paramount in meeting their human rights. All DFID programmes that include people with physical disabilities should adhere to the WHO Guidelines for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Manual Wheelchairs in Less Resourced Settings (2008) and associated training packages. These internationally recognised resources outline the steps necessary to ensure appropriate assistive devices for beneficiaries, develop wheelchair services in clinic s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ettings and community-based rehabilitation, and to train local medical professionals for the treatment of patients with mobility disabilities. Other development agencies have begun using the WHO guidelines across their programmes, but major change cannot o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ccur without DFID commitment. It is crucial that DFID adopts these guidelines and leads the way, acting as a role model in the development community by using appropriate mobility products, services and training as a key part of its international strategy. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The impact assessment (highlighted above) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">identified the need for the improvement of wheelchair services, particularly the follow-up of beneficiaries and the increase of networks offering a range of support to individuals with mobility disabilities. The ap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">propriate assistive device was a crucial step for the beneficiaries, but only the first one in a series of needed actions. Further support and services are required in order to support people with mobility disabilities to reach their full potential. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a major opportunity for DFID to acknowledge and embrace the vital importance of the role assistive devices play in the lives of disabled people around the world, and to truly fulfil its mission of assisting the most vulnerable and in need. Without clos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">er attention paid to disability, and assistive devices in particular, it will be impossible for development goals to succeed, and progress will halt in places where it is most required. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> UNCRPD, </span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt">3 May 2008 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:10pt"> World Health Organisation, 2011</span></p></body></html>